<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,714,1444]" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">
Distribution. Native to North 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Flechtmann &amp; Cognato" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[491,590,714,740]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="America" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">America</taxonomicName>
, distributed throughout the northern portions of eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1234,1387,714,740]" name="United States of America" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">United States</collectingCountry>
and southeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[298,382,749,775]" name="Canada" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">Canada</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Wood, S. L. &amp; Bright, D. E. Jr." box="[395,636,749,775]" pageId="15" pageNumber="66" pagination="1 - 1553" refId="ref19640" refString="Wood, S. L. &amp; Bright, D. E. Jr. (1992) A catalog of Scolytidae and Platypodidae (Coleoptera), part 2: Taxonomic index. Great Basin Naturalist Memoirs, 13, 1 - 1553." type="journal article" year="1992">Wood &amp; Bright 1992</bibRefCitation>
). 
<collectingCountry box="[655,731,750,776]" name="France" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">France</collectingCountry>
is the first European country colonized by this species. Report-ed in Seine-Maritime for the first time in 
<quantity box="[604,688,784,810]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.12318" pageId="15" pageNumber="66" unit="in" value="2017.0">2017 in</quantity>
a blog (
<bibRefCitation author="Dodelin, B. &amp; Saurat, R." box="[774,1037,784,810]" pageId="15" pageNumber="66" refId="ref14654" refString="Dodelin, B. &amp; Saurat, R. (2017) Xyloterinus politus a traverse l'Atlantique. EntomoData. Available from: https: // entomodata. wordpress. com / 2017 / 07 / 08 / xyloterinus-politus-a-traverse-latlantique / (accessed 1 March 2019)" type="url" year="2017">Dodelin &amp; Saurat 2017</bibRefCitation>
), its presence was then confirmed in a forest of the same department. Given the current distribution, 
<taxonomicName box="[862,969,819,845]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Xyloterinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="politus">
<emphasis box="[862,969,819,845]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">X. politus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
likely entered the French territory via the port of Le Havre. Although so far only few individuals have been captured, the presence in a natural forest suggests it is established in 
<collectingCountry box="[360,440,890,916]" name="France" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">France</collectingCountry>
. However, for the moment 
<taxonomicName box="[745,852,890,916]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Xyloterinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="politus">
<emphasis box="[745,852,890,916]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">X. politus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to be a non-aggressive and rare species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,714,1444]" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">
Literature records: 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[416,684,925,951]" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">SEINE-MARITIME –</emphasis>
Near Le Havre, PNR of the Boucles de la Seine Normande, interception trap, 2017, 2 ind. (
<bibRefCitation author="Dodelin, B. &amp; Saurat, R." box="[456,730,960,986]" pageId="15" pageNumber="66" refId="ref14654" refString="Dodelin, B. &amp; Saurat, R. (2017) Xyloterinus politus a traverse l'Atlantique. EntomoData. Available from: https: // entomodata. wordpress. com / 2017 / 07 / 08 / xyloterinus-politus-a-traverse-latlantique / (accessed 1 March 2019)" type="url" year="2017">Dodelin &amp; Saurat 2017</bibRefCitation>
); Near Le Havre, PNR of the Boucles de la Seine Normande, caught on a young and died field maple, 
<date box="[608,757,996,1022]" pageId="15" pageNumber="66" value="2017-08-08">08.VIII.2017</date>
, 
<specimenCount box="[768,810,996,1022]" pageId="15" pageNumber="66" type="female">1 ♀</specimenCount>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Dodelin, B. &amp; Saurat, R." box="[824,1092,995,1022]" pageId="15" pageNumber="66" refId="ref14654" refString="Dodelin, B. &amp; Saurat, R. (2017) Xyloterinus politus a traverse l'Atlantique. EntomoData. Available from: https: // entomodata. wordpress. com / 2017 / 07 / 08 / xyloterinus-politus-a-traverse-latlantique / (accessed 1 March 2019)" type="url" year="2017">Dodelin &amp; Saurat 2017</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,714,1444]" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">
New records: 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,581,1030,1057]" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">SEINE-MARITIME –</emphasis>
Vatteville-la-Rue, FD Brotonne, RBI des Landes, interception traps baited with ethanol 20%, from 
<date box="[424,636,1066,1093]" pageId="15" pageNumber="66" value="2018-05-15" valueMax="2018-05-29" valueMin="2018-05-15">15.V. to 29.V.2018</date>
, 1 ind., S. Etienne 
<emphasis box="[847,888,1066,1092]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">leg.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,714,1444]" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">
Biology and Ecology. In its native range, 
<taxonomicName box="[669,777,1101,1127]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Xyloterinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="politus">
<emphasis box="[669,777,1101,1127]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">X. politus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is highly polyphagous and has been recorded from a wide variety of angiosperm families, and has even been collected from conifers; in the eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1175,1224,1136,1162]" name="United States of America" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">U.S.</collectingCountry>
it is said to attack mainly 
<taxonomicName box="[235,339,1172,1198]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="15" pageNumber="66" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fagaceae</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[354,448,1172,1198]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="15" pageNumber="66" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[354,448,1172,1198]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">Quercus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[500,570,1172,1197]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Fagus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="15" pageNumber="66" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[500,570,1172,1197]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">Fagus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="MacLean, D. B. &amp; Giese, R. L." box="[592,863,1171,1198]" pageId="15" pageNumber="66" pagination="285 - 299" refId="ref17320" refString="MacLean, D. B. &amp; Giese, R. L. (1967) The life history of ambrosia beetle Xyloterinus politus (Coleoptera Scolytidae). The Canadian Entomologist, 99 (3), 285 - 299. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / Ent 99285 - 3" type="journal article" year="1967">MacLean &amp; Giese 1967</bibRefCitation>
).Although in 
<collectingCountry box="[1018,1094,1172,1198]" name="France" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">France</collectingCountry>
this species has been observed only on field maple (
<taxonomicName authorityName="C.Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" box="[382,555,1207,1233]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Acer" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="15" pageNumber="66" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="campestre">
<emphasis box="[382,555,1207,1233]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">Acer campestre</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L.) (
<bibRefCitation author="Dodelin, B. &amp; Saurat, R." box="[608,872,1207,1233]" pageId="15" pageNumber="66" refId="ref14654" refString="Dodelin, B. &amp; Saurat, R. (2017) Xyloterinus politus a traverse l'Atlantique. EntomoData. Available from: https: // entomodata. wordpress. com / 2017 / 07 / 08 / xyloterinus-politus-a-traverse-latlantique / (accessed 1 March 2019)" type="url" year="2017">Dodelin &amp; Saurat 2017</bibRefCitation>
), its host range should ultimately be much broader. In the 
<collectingCountry box="[225,380,1242,1268]" name="United States of America" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">United States</collectingCountry>
, this ambrosia beetle colonizes very weak or recently dead trees, with a preference for fallen trunks (
<bibRefCitation author="MacLean, D. B. &amp; Giese, R. L." box="[236,510,1277,1304]" pageId="15" pageNumber="66" pagination="285 - 299" refId="ref17320" refString="MacLean, D. B. &amp; Giese, R. L. (1967) The life history of ambrosia beetle Xyloterinus politus (Coleoptera Scolytidae). The Canadian Entomologist, 99 (3), 285 - 299. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / Ent 99285 - 3" type="journal article" year="1967">MacLean &amp; Giese 1967</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,714,1444]" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">
Damage and infestation risk. In North 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Flechtmann &amp; Cognato" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[627,723,1312,1338]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="America" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">America</taxonomicName>
this species is considered a secondary pest, so it is unlikely that it will become a phytosanitary threat in 
<collectingCountry box="[603,682,1348,1374]" name="France" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">France</collectingCountry>
, even though behavioral changes of invasive alien species arriving in new environments and experiencing changes in climate cannot be excluded (
<bibRefCitation author="Kuhnholz, S. &amp; Borden, J. H. &amp; Uzunovic, A." box="[1034,1274,1383,1409]" pageId="15" pageNumber="66" pagination="209 - 219" refId="ref17108" refString="Kuhnholz, S., Borden, J. H. &amp; Uzunovic, A. (2001) Secondary ambrosia beetles in apparently healthy trees: adaptations, potential causes and suggested research. Integrated Pest Management Reviews, 6, 209 - 219. https: // doi. org / 10.1023 / A: 1025702930580" type="journal article" year="2001">
Kühnholz 
<emphasis box="[1152,1208,1383,1409]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="66">et al.</emphasis>
2001
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Knizek, M." box="[1285,1431,1383,1409]" pageId="15" pageNumber="66" pagination="101 - 104" refId="ref16961" refString="Knizek, M. (2007) Bark and ambrosia beetle species in worldwide trade. In: Evans, H. &amp; Oszako, T. (Eds.), Alien Invasive Species and International Trade. Forest Research Institute, Warsaw, pp. 101 - 104. https: // doi. org / 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0158519" type="book chapter" year="2007">Knižek 2007</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hulcr, J. &amp; Dunn, R." box="[151,380,1418,1444]" pageId="15" pageNumber="66" pagination="2866 - 2873" refId="ref16105" refString="Hulcr, J. &amp; Dunn, R. (2011) The sudden emergence of pathogenicity in insect-fungus symbioses threatens native forest ecosystems. Proceeding of the Royal Society of London, 2078, 2866 - 2873. https: // doi. org / 10.1098 / rspb. 2011.1130" type="journal article" year="2011">Hulcr &amp; Dunn 2011</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
